y and connection to the centre drove relations between towns and the crown in this period, as borough governments actively sought strong ties with central authority while also attempting to preserve their chartered liberties. It also argues that the 1620s and 1630s ushered in new patterns in the crown's relations with incorporated boroughs, as Charles I's regime hardened policies towards urban localities. Based on extensive original research in both central government records and the archives of a wide range of provincial towns, the book covers critical aspects of interaction between towns and the crown, including incorporation and charters, governance and political order, social regulation, trade, financial and military exactions, and religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCentral-local government relationsy17th centuryzEngland. 0aCentral-local government relationszEnglandy17th century. 0aLocal governmenty17th centuryzEngland. 0aLocal governmentzEnglandy17th century. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aEngland.  acentral authority.  acorporate liberties.  acrown relations.  aearly Stuart government.  alocal autonomy.  apolitical order.  aprovincial towns.  aroyal authority.  aurban governance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311143099740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800104969?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800104969423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800104969/original  a978-3-11-143099-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles